# Mathematics still to be completed
#
# Chapters 1-3 — foundational linear algebra
# The remaining gaps are the selected complex and vector-space structures,
# finite-list exchange and basis theorems, matrix/rank constructions, quotient
# well-definedness, inverse selection, and dual-space constructions. The
# source-facing definitions and results are present, but these constructions
# and proofs have not all been supplied.
#
# Chapter 4 — polynomial factorization
# The coordinate complex-number laws, polynomial representation and division,
# and the analytic minimum-modulus argument used by the fundamental theorem of
# algebra still need complete proofs.
#
# Chapter 5, Sections 5A-5E — operators
# The finite-sum algebra for polynomial evaluation, minimal-polynomial
# existence and consequences, invariant restrictions, triangularization,
# diagonalization, eigenspace dimension arguments, Gershgorin's theorem, and
# simultaneous-basis results still contain unproved mathematical steps.
#
# Chapter 6, Sections 6A-6C — inner-product spaces
# The scalar-geometry instances, norm inequalities, Gram-Schmidt and Riesz
# constructions, orthogonal decompositions and projections, and pseudoinverse
# results retain incomplete existence or proof steps.
#
# Chapter 7, Section 7A — Results 7.5-7.23
# The adjoint construction is uniquely characterized, and Result 7.4 is
# checked. The adjoint algebra, null/range identities, self-adjoint criteria,
# and normal-operator consequences still need their full proofs.
#
# Chapter 7, Section 7B — Results 7.26, 7.27, 7.29, and 7.31
# The four source statements and the concrete calculations in Examples 7.30
# and 7.33 are present. The quadratic positivity proof, real factor elimination, and the
# real and complex spectral-theorem arguments remain to be completed.
#
# Chapter 7, Section 7C — Results 7.38, 7.39, and 7.43
# Positivity, square-root candidacy, the six-way characterization, exact unique
# existence, callable square-root notation, and the three checked source
# examples are present. The spectral construction and uniqueness proof remain,
# as does the two-move proof of 7.43. The callable positive-square-root selector
